// =====================================================================
// D0105 (PROPOSED — NOT YET ACCEPTED) — adopt declarative, model-driven controls: collapse the
// bespoke per-defect Rust guards into a small generic evaluator over DECLARED rules. ~8 of 14 guards
// are one assertion in disguise ("a downstream instance must carry its declared upstream edge to an
// existing element"); the other ~5 are per-element integrity predicates. Replace both with declared
// `EdgeRule`/`ElementRule` elements (SysML, fork #1) evaluated generically by `keel check`, plus a
// CLOSED RMWX verb axis for writes. Code stops growing per-defect (rules -> infinity, code -> flat).
// Design artifact: docs/proposals/2026-06-30-declarative-controls-issue054.md. status=proposed:
// this CAPTURES the direction the human endorsed in analysis; ACCEPTANCE awaits the Change-Request +
// schema/core human sign-off (a `Rule` type is a frozen-core addition). Drives issue054 + issue055.
// =====================================================================
package Decision0105 {
    private import EngineElement::*;
    private import EngineWork::*;
    private import EngineVerification::*;
    private import EngineRelationships::*;

    part d0105 : Decision {
        :>> id = "05a1b0c1-4105-42a3-ab5c-516273849705";
        :>> title = "D0105 (PROPOSED): declarative, model-driven controls — collapse bespoke guards into declared rules";
        :>> createdAt = "2026-06-30";
        :>> createdBy = "claudeOpus";
        :>> status = DecisionStatus::proposed;
        :>> context = "The engine enforces invariants with bespoke hand-compiled Rust guards, one per defect class. The set grew 12->13->14 (D0102/D0103) and issue054 proposed a 15th; D0047 ('every correction becomes a permanent guard') institutionalizes this reactive growth. Three smells: (1) GUARD SPRAWL — the control surface grows linearly with discovered defects. (2) CLI-VERB PROLIFERATION — add-task/append-result/apply-review/proposed-add-decision: one verb per authored type, coupling the CLI to the schema. (3) DUPLICATED TRUTH — business.sysml already DECLARES the workflow order (first needs then useCases); a hand-written ordering guard re-encodes that truth in Rust, the anti-pattern Sec 2.1 forbids. ANALYSIS FINDING (proven): sorting the 14 guards by what they ACTUALLY assert, ~8 of 14 reduce to ONE assertion — 'a downstream instance must carry its declared upstream edge to an existing element' (ceremony/sprint-coverage/requirement-rootedness/issues/process-skill/charter/process-change/decision-requirement-link). The other ~5 (actors/decision-rationale/critic-independence/manifest-coverage/viewpoint-renderer) are per-element integrity predicates. Separately, the Business/Architecture workflows are INERT (no deploying skill, contra D0059; the process-skill guard scans only .engine/processes/, not .engine/workflows/), which is the real root of issue054 F1; and `keel serve` has no Business/Needs view. Full design: docs/proposals/2026-06-30-declarative-controls-issue054.md.";
        :>> decision = "Adopt DECLARATIVE, MODEL-DRIVEN controls evaluated generically — not coded. (a) Two declared rule shapes, first-class SysML elements with UUID identity carrying a `justifiedBy` edge to the Decision that justifies them: `EdgeRule` (subject type/marker + required edge + object type + cardinality + scope + severity) subsumes the ~8 conformance guards; `ElementRule` (subject type + a predicate composed from a CLOSED vocabulary of primitives — nonBlank/minLength/matchesPattern/inRegistry/distinct/referentExists/resolvesToCommand/countCompare) subsumes the ~5 structural guards. (b) ORDERING needs no new schema — the evaluator consumes the already-declared workflow succession at instance level. (c) A single `keel check` evaluates whatever the model declares, replacing the forever-growing `guard <name>`. (d) A CLOSED RMWX verb axis (read/record/modify/execute), each generic over the model, replaces the per-type write verbs; triage becomes (verb x targetType)->process. FORK #1 RESOLVED: rules live as SysML elements (single source of truth, native provenance, critique-able/suspect-able/coverage-counted), and the TOML contracts (critique-policy.toml, reverify.toml) are RECONCILED into the model (governance->Rule; pure execution params referenced BY a Rule), not extended. The friction objection is killed by the generic `record` verb.";
        :>> rationale = "ALTERNATIVES: (i) status quo — keep adding one Rust guard + one CLI verb per defect — REJECTED (proven 8x duplication; sprawl; downstream projects inherit this repo's defect history with no opt-out). (ii) 'one process to rule them all' (enforce only workflow conformance) — REJECTED as INSUFFICIENT (covers ordering/edge-conformance but NOT per-element integrity; those don't vanish — they become ElementRules). (iii) declare rules in TOML (extend the existing contracts) — REJECTED (second store -> drift; no typed provenance edge; opaque to critique/suspicion/coverage; no identity). (iv) CHOSEN — SysML-declared EdgeRule/ElementRule + generic evaluator + closed verb axis: strictly more faithful to the engine's own invariants (Sec 2.1 text-is-truth; Sec 2.6 reference-don't-embed; D0088 requirements-as-evaluable-constraints), and justified BECAUSE keel is a reusable multi-project engine (downstream declares its own rules, enforcement free). CRITERIA: single-source-of-truth x flat-code-growth x downstream-flexibility x faithful-to-invariants x honest-state-preserved.";
        :>> consequences = "schema/core gains `Rule`/`EdgeRule`/`ElementRule` + a predicate vocabulary — FROZEN-CORE additions requiring HUMAN SIGN-OFF before any code (this is why status=proposed). MIGRATION via D0067 (expand/migrate/contract) with a PARITY GATE: build the evaluator alongside the 14 guards, express each as a rule, prove `keel check` output == the guards' output on the current repo, THEN retire the Rust predicates (precedent: the retired python/rust parity check). REFRAMES D0047 (corrections become declared RULES, not new code). EXTENDS D0088 (the constraint layer becomes declared ElementRules). The D0068 charter-wording amendment is tracked separately (issue055/analysisChartersResearchSpike). SUBSUMES issue054's resolver (ordering becomes a declared EdgeRule, not `guard ordering`; add-decision becomes the generic `record` verb). Honest-state vs completeness (D0098) is preserved: blocking rules are honest-state gates; completeness stays non-blocking burndown. The edge algebra stays CLOSED. doc-sync: CLAUDE.md Sec 3 (triage axes) + Sec 5 (guard enumeration -> `keel check`). Tracked work: declarativeControlsEvaluator, guardsToRulesMigration, businessArchSkillAndWorkflowGuard, serveBusinessNeedsView (EngineBacklog).";
    }
}
